arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized in seven series: Personal; Calendars and appointment books; Subject files; Correspondence; Phone calls; Publications and press; Visual materials.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This collection was processed by Jennifer Phillips in 2006, supervised by Susanne Belovari. Processing notes: Weeding of the collection was not systematic, but was done if the following items were spotted: duplicates of publications, speeches, news clippings, newsletters, etc.; Tufts publications; empty file folders. The following preservation measures were taken: refoldering, replacing rusty staples and paper clips; photocopying of thermal FAXES, particularly from the "Subject Files" and "Correspondence" series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Collection materials include: agendas, appointment books, brochures, correspondence (letters and faxes), itineraries, newspaper and journal clippings, phone call logs, photos, publications, reports, receipts, slides, speech scripts, video.

Functions or activities represented: academic administrative functions, meeting and conference organization (NEEN, EAEN, IUCN), publishing, research, professional networking, and environmental activism.

Significant topics, events, places: local, national, and international environmental organizations; environmental forums and events; environmental legislation; conferences; Africa, Armenia, Australia, Canada, China, India, Massachusetts, Oregon, Russia, Washington.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Nancy W. Anderson (August 7, 1922-November 11, 1997) received a BA in Public Administration from George Washington University in 1944.

Before coming to Tufts, Anderson served as an officer in WAVES (Women Accepted for Volunteer Emergency Service) (1944-46), in part as a Medical Librarian at Bethesda. From 1947 to 1949 she was an Informational Control Officer for the CIA. Her environmental work began in the early 1970s when she volunteered for the Massachusetts Association of Conservation Commissions (MACC) and started editing their newsletter. At that time she also became the Chairman of the Reading Conservation Commission, which looked at water supply and flood plain conservation issues. Because of this work, Anderson Meadow in Reading was named in her honor. She also served as a consultant for the Massachusetts Institute of Governmental Services at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, helping them to organize environmental evening classes. Beginning in 1975, she acted as coordinator for the Environmental Citizen Advocacy Program, a joint venture of the Lincoln Filene Center and the Tufts program in Environmental Policy.

From 1978 to 1994, Anderson was the Director of Environmental Affairs at the Lincoln Filene Center (LFC). In 1979 she founded the New England Environmental Network (NEEN), an educational network for those concerned about the environment. While at Tufts (1978-1994), she was active in the International Union for the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) and served as the Regional Chairman for their Commission on Education and Communication. In 1989 (or 1990), she co-founded the Eastern Africa Environmental Network to organize environmental educational programs for Africa. Anderson received numerous environmental and citizenship awards and was a sought-after speaker on topics related to the environment and environmental activism. Her publications ranged from newsletters and short articles to handbooks and conference summaries. She also served as an advisor or director for countless environmental organizations, including Grand Circle Travel, Environmental Lobby of Massachusetts, Save the Harbor/Save the Bay, the Coolidge Center for Environmental Leadership, the Water Supply Citizens Advisory Committee, and the Coalition for Environmentally Responsible Economics.

In 1993, Anderson became a Senior Fellow at the LFC, a part-time position. She continued to represent the LFC at the IUCN and served as an honorary Chairman of the EAEN. Her ongoing activism included serving on President Clinton's Council on Sustainable Development.

Anderson retired from the LFC on June 30, 1994. She moved to Maine with her husband but continued her environmental work as a Research Associate for the Global/International Environment and Project Institute at the Tufts Fletcher School of Diplomacy. She also served as a board member for the Senior College at the University of Southern Maine, where she taught courses on Environmental Awareness.

Nancy W. Anderson died on November 11, 1997 at the age of 75. She was survived by Col. John A. Anderson (U.S.M.C. ret.), her husband of 49 years, and two children, Nancy C. Anderson and John A. Anderson, Jr.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains biographical information. This series brings together various folders found in NWA's subject files originally labeled "NWA personal," "personal," and "profiles." This series contains passports, curriculum vitas, personal profiles, retirement related material, as well as get well cards and condolences sent to NWA's husband upon her death. The folder labeled "Vita and current articles" is one of NWA's original folders and shows how she represented herself.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains bound appointment books for the years between 1974 and 1997, except 1980, 1981, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1988, and 1993. These appointment books usually span the academic calendar, although in some cases they span the calendar year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series includes files pertaining to: organizations of which NWA was a member; conferences and events; places and institutions where she gave presentations; professional contacts; environmental concerns. NWA kept more than one alphabetized series for recent and older files. During processing we decided to merge all subject files into one alphabetized series to assist researchers and because the various chronological subject series overlapped extensively. After processing was completed, we discovered that one box of additional subject files had not been accessioned. These files, ranging from 'M' to 'W', were added at the end of the alphabetized run of subject files.

Subject files generally retain original titles, but dates were added when missing. Titles were added or changed for speeches and some un-filed material. NWA sometimes filed her speeches under "A" for addresses and organized them alphabetically by sponsor. For ease of access, speeches were moved to "S" for "Speeches." In some cases NWA filed her speeches under the sponsoring organization; these speeches remain in the original location. Users are advised to search under "Speeches" and relevant subject files.

Most un-filed material was filed in their appropriate subject files based on original sticky notes indicating to which file they belonged. In two cases, un-filed material was unlabeled and we created the following subject files: MACC Environmental Education Task Force; Reading Open Land Trust.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence of NWA as Director of Environmental Affairs and Senior Fellow at LFC, and as a Research Associate in the Fletcher School. When NWA filed or bound her correspondence, she often organized it in reverse chronological order, and bound and unbound correspondence usually overlapped chronologically and alphabetically. No attempt was made to interfile these. Un-filed letters were filed under "Miscellaneous Correspondence" (1975-1989).
Correspondence also contains receipts, newspaper clippings, or other printed material.

arrangement.p: This series is arranged according to original order.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains assorted published material. Publications either were un-filed or filed under "P" in the original subject files.

Sub-series 1, "NWA authored publications": This sub-series contains articles and pamphlets written by NWA (some of them un-filed) and includes the MACC newsletter which NWA edited for approximately 10 years. NWA usually filed articles and pamphlets in her subject files under "P" with overly broad file names such as "Publications," "Publicity," and "Articles." For ease of use, these were moved to the publication series during processing.

Sub-series 2, "Publications about NWA": This sub-series contains newspaper and journal articles about NWA or for which she was interviewed, as well as publications for which she was consulted. Many of these folders were originally filed in the subject files under "Publicity."

Sub-series 3, "Publications and press": This sub-series contains un-filed books, brochures, conference proceedings, flyers, journals, newsletters, position papers, and reports dealing with environmental topics and organizations. Publications and press material are also in subject files, e.g., filed under creating agency or appropriate environmental topic. Material filed in this way was left in its subject file. Users are advised to consult both the publication series as well as relevant subject files.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is grouped into three sub-series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains un-filed photos, slides, negative proofs, and a video. There were two photo albums with pictures from the EAEN conference in 1994. Most other photographs and negatives were found in envelopes, sometimes dated but unlabeled. Photos found loose in boxes were put in a folder titled "Miscellaneous Photographs."

One group of labeled slides was taken in Yerevan, USSR, 1989. One group of slides was unlabeled but presumably taken in the Indian sub-continent. One carrel of slides was labeled "Africa Show." The second carrel of slides was unlabeled but was presumably taken in Africa. Total number of slides: 256.
The video is from the University of Southern Maine and is titled "Senior College U.S.M. 3-4/97."

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged loosely chronologically.
